---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={`About — ${SITE_TITLE}`} description="About After Two Thirty" />
		<style>
			.prose {
				max-width: 620px;
				width: 100%;
				margin: 0 auto;
			}
			.page-title {
				font-family: var(--font-display);
				font-size: 2.2rem;
				font-weight: 700;
				margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
				letter-spacing: -0.01em;
			}
			.page-divider {
				width: 100%;
				height: 1px;
				background: var(--color-border);
				margin: 1rem 0 2.5rem;
			}
			.prose p {
				margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
				font-size: 1rem;
				line-height: 1.85;
			}
			.prose p.break {
				margin-bottom: 2.2rem;
			}
			@media (max-width: 600px) {
				.page-title {
					font-size: 1.8rem;
				}
			}
		</style>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<article>
				<div class="prose">
					<h1 class="page-title">About</h1>
					<div class="page-divider"></div>

					<p>I am a mother of twin girls, Vicky and Sydney.</p>

					<p>They experience the world a little differently, and raising them has shaped the way I see childhood, learning, and the small signals children carry on their faces.</p>

					<p>Many afternoons, I stand at the school gate watching the children come out. Some walk in groups, talking and laughing. Some walk quietly. In those moments I often find myself observing not only my daughters, but childhood itself.</p>

					<p>Our family also happens to live close to the world of artificial intelligence. My husband is an AI engineer, and at home we sometimes experiment with a small AI research system that tracks how technology and education are changing.</p>

					<p class="break">Because of that, I often feel that our family is standing near the edge of a new era — watching how the world children are growing into is quietly transforming.</p>

					<p>This website grew out of those observations.</p>

					<p><strong>After Two Thirty</strong> tells the small stories that happen after the school gate opens — the walk to the car, the questions, the silence, the laughter, and the slow work of raising children.</p>

					<p class="break"><strong>Before Two Thirty</strong> looks at the changing world children are growing into — how technology, education, and artificial intelligence may shape the future they will inherit.</p>

					<p>I am not writing as an expert.</p>

					<p>I am writing as a mother who is watching, learning, and trying to understand the world my daughters will grow up in.</p>
				</div>
			</article>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
